Medical Appointment No Shows¶

Kaggle Dataset

Introduction¶

In this project we'll be analysing data associated with the medical appointments in Brazil and the focus is on question whether or not patients show up for their appointments. Also, we'll be interested in finding the factors that are important for us to know in order to predict if a patient will show up for their scheduled appointment.

Data Dictionary¶

1. PatientId: Identification of a patient 
2. AppointmentID: Identification of each appointment 
3. Gender: Male or Female . Female is the greater proportion, woman takes way more care of they health in comparison to man. 
4. AppointmentDay: The day of the actual appointment, when they have to visit the doctor. 
5. ScheduledDay: The day someone called or registered the appointment, this is before appointment of course. 
6. Age: How old is the patient. 
7. Neighbourhood: Where the appointment takes place. 
8. Scholarship: Ture of False . Observation, this is a broad topic, consider reading this article https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bolsa_Fam%C3%ADlia 
9. Hipertension: True or False 
10. Diabetes: True or False 
11. Alcoholism: True or False 
12. Handcap: True or False 
13. SMS_received: 1 or more messages sent to the patient. 
14. No-show: True or False. It says ‘No’ if the patient showed up to their appointment, and ‘Yes’ if they did not show up.

Observations:¶

1. There are a total of 110527 rows and 14 columns in the dataset. The dataset do not contain any missing values or duplicate records.

2. The descriptive statistics and the histogram shows that the age column has a minimum value of -1 which is impossible as age cannot be negative and a maximum of 115 years which denotes the outlier in the age column. Also, the age showed as 0 for a considerable amount of people who had taken the appointment. We will not remove the age having the value as 0 as these might be new born babies having their appointments with the doctor.

3. From the histogram of Handcap, the bandwith shows the value from 0 to 4 while the data dictionary tells that handcap can only be 0 or 1.

At the discussion forum, it is explained by the data creator that the handicap values denotes the number of disabilites the patient have.

4. The values for alcoholism, diabetes, sms_received and scholarship are either 0 or 1 which signifies whether the patient is diabetic, alcoholic, and so on.

5. Although, the columns containing 0 or 1 are numerical columns in the dataset but 0 or 1 are treated as categorical variables which we will convert later in the process. 

6. Out of the 110527 patients, only 47.28 % had received the SMS for their appointment. It is unclear as why not all of the patients have received the SMS.

7. From the statistics, it can be observed that maximum number of women's had taken the appointments in comparison to male.

8. From the statistics, it can be observed that most of the people resides near the JARDIM CAMBURI.

It’s a good idea to convert string data types to categorical because this data type helps us save some memory by making the dataframe smaller. The memory usage of categorical variables is proportional to the number of categories + the length of the data.

By exploring the patientid column, we found that a single patient has booked appointments multiple times and he showed/didn't show in some of them. Let's create a new column with the proportion of noshow vs total number of appointments by the same patients.

Q2. What is the ratio of categorical characteristics of the dataset and the no_show characteristic?¶

In order to answer this question we will find the ratio against each of the following categorical characteristics:
    1. Gender
    2. Scholarship
    3. Hypertension
    4. Diabetes
    5. Alcoholism
    6. Handicap

Let's begin with:
  • Gender
In [48]:
# Define a function to plot ratio of categorical characteristics of the dataset and the no_show characteristic
def cat_plots(col,plabel,ptitle,pglabel,pgtitle):   
    # Subplots
    figs, axes = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(8,8))
    plt.subplots_adjust(left=0.12, right=1.7, wspace=0.5, hspace=0.5)
    # Pie Chart
    df[col].value_counts().plot(kind='pie', autopct='%.2f%%', explode=(0.05,0), 
                                labels=plabel, colors=['mediumseagreen','y'], ax=axes[0])
    axes[0].set_title(ptitle)
    # Pie Chart: Categorical characteristics and No_Show characteristic
    df[col].groupby(df['no_show']).value_counts().plot(kind='pie', autopct='%.2f%%', explode=(0.05,0.05,0,0),
                                   labels=pglabel, colors=['#228B22','#2E8B57','#F0E68C','#BDB76B'], ax=axes[1])
    axes[1].set_title(pgtitle)
    plt.show()
    
def count_plots(col, clabel, ctitle):
    # Count Plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(7,5))
    sns.countplot(df[col], hue=df['no_show'], palette='Set2')
    plt.xticks(ticks=[0,1], labels=clabel)
    plt.title(ctitle)
    plt.show()

From the above charts, it can be seen clearly that in the given dataset of 100K records, 65.00% patients are female while 35.00% patients are male. Gender donot have an overall impact on the dataset as the distribution is skewed towards women. Also, the females who didn't show up are approximately doubled (13.20%) in comparision to males (6.99%) who didn't show up.
